{A very warm welcome to everyone! This is IM Kushager Krishnater and I present to you a complete repertoire for White on the unexplored 1.d4 Nf6 2.c4 e6 3.Bg5!? variation. Modern opening preparation is evolving. White players are not looking for an objective advantage anymore. Instead, surprising the opponent early out in the opening and trying to catch-them offguard is all the rage these days. That's what we want to accomplish with this course. With 3.Bg5, White wants to take Black in unchartered territory. There are several pitfalls for Black and even if they play good chess, the resulting positions offer great dynamic chances to both sides. We would avoid long & boring theoretical battles with this move but instead, apply psychological pressure on our opponent from Move 3 onwards!} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Bg5 {We threaten e4. White retains flexibility between Nc3 & Nd2 here. This setup is annoying for all players except the ones who play the Queen's Gambit Declined. Black has a lot of choices here. Let me take you through the covered directions briefly.} Bb4+ {This is what I would expect a Ragozin player to play. However, after} ({The Benoni approach against 3.Bg5 makes a great deal of sense. Here, I propose playing} 3... c5 4. d5 {and after} exd5 5. cxd5 d6 6. e4 h6 {White has the strong} 7. Be3 $5 {[%cal Gd1a4,Ga4e4,Rf6e4] the e4-pawn remains defended tactically. There's a lot of subtle nuances to know for both sides.}) (3... h6 {throwing this in also makes a great deal of sense.} 4. Bh4 {after this move, they have two logical ideas (apart from transposing to the QGD lines with ...d5/...Be7 or Ragozin lines with ...Bb4).} g5 $5 {sharpening up the position.} ({Black can also opt for the Benoni approach with} 4... c5 {White's play remains consistent.} 5. d5 exd5 6. cxd5 d6 7. e4 Be7 {and here, I propose playing} 8. Bg3 O-O 9. Nd2 {[%cal Gg1e2,Ge2c3] if given a chance, we would love to play Ne2-Nc3. The position remains full of life and your opponent most likely would be out of prep here.}) 5. Bg3 {[%cal Gf2f3,Rb1c3] we'll play Nc3 or f3 next. The position often remains highly imbalanced with all 3 results to fight for.}) (3... d5 {Chapters 7-13 are focused exclusively on the Queen's Gambit Declined setup with ...d5. Against almost all of their setups, I propose fresh & testing ideas.} 4. cxd5 exd5 5. Nc3 {they have four decent options here.} Be7 {the standard approach.} ({This is my recommendation in one of the other courses for Black on Modern Chess. As White, I propose playing out a concept that is very topical in these structures.} 5... Be6 6. e3 Nbd7 7. Bd3 c6 {This is the main tabiya of the 5...Be6 system. Here, I propose playing} 8. h3 Be7 9. Bf4 $5 {sliding the bishop over to the active diagonal. Modern engines have taught us that the dark-squared bishop belong on the b8-h2 diagonal. My recommendation is original and full of life.}) ({Against the enterprising} 5... Bb4 {I propose playing} 6. e3 h6 7. Bf4 $5 {looking to play in the 'QGD' fashion. White keeps control and there's a lot of ways for Black to go wrong here.}) (5... c6 6. e3 Bf5 {this is played by players who are looking to create a fortress after 7.Qf3 Bg6 8.Bxf6 Qxf6 9.Qxf6 gxf6. Instead, I recommend} ({options like} 6... Bd6 {are also covered in the final chapter of the course.}) 7. Bd3 $5 Bxd3 8. Qxd3 {[%cal Gf2f3,Ge3e4] preparing a potential f3-e4. White keeps control and a lot of chances to gain an objective advantage here.}) 6. e3 h6 7. Bh4 c6 {This is what I call the absolute main line of the QGD. Here, I propose playing} ({against Carlsen's} 7... Bg4 {I recommend playing} 8. Qc2 O-O {and now the rare} 9. h3 Be6 10. Nge2 $5 {[%cal Ge2f4] preparing Nf4. White keeps very easy play here.}) 8. Bd3 O-O 9. Bg3 $5 {[%cal Gg3b8] sliding the bishop over to the b8-h2 diagonal, something which we regularly do against the QGD. This is quite fresh and offers good chances to obtain an advantage for White.}) 4. Nd2 $5 {they are already out of preparation! Imagine catching your opponent off-guard on the 4th move in a position where there all pieces on the board! While the engine throws zeroes here, the lines can be incredibly complex. There are several ways for your opponent to go wrong here.} *

