{Welcome to the first chapter. We begin our exploration of the 3.Bg5!? variation by checking out the dynamic 3 ...Bb4 4.Nd2 h6 5.Bh4 variation.} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Bg5 {[%cal Gg5d8] we develop our bishop out early here. This helps us retain flexibility between the c3 & the d2 square for our knight. Of course, there's a certain drawback to it. The bishop can be vulnerable of g5.} Bb4+ {Black is hoping for a transposition to Nimzo/Ragozin lines.} 4. Nd2 $5 {This was the surprise that we had planned! We don't give them the opportunity to spoil our pawn structure with ...Bxc3. We are already in a fresh territory where your opponent most likely would have been unprepared.} h6 {The most logical response as Black. They want to kick our bishop away.} 5. Bh4 {[%cal Gh4d8] maintaining the pressure for the meanwhile. This is the first branching point of the current chapter.} g5 {The most ambitious move. They weaken their Kingside a bit to side-step the pin and to play ...Ne4 next.} (5... c5 6. dxc5 Qa5 $6 {the only independent try. However, this runs into} (6... Nc6 7. Ngf3 Bxc5 8. e3 O-O 9. Be2 {transposes to the next chapter.}) (6... Bxc5 7. e3 {transposes to the next chapter.}) 7. Bxf6 $14 {where we end up being better due to our pawn structure.}) (5... d5 6. Rc1 {transposes to the next chapter.}) (5... b6 {allows the opportunity to go for their bishop with} 6. a3 Bxd2+ 7. Qxd2 Bb7 8. f3 $1 $14 {[%csl Rb7] effectively neutralising their bishop on b7. We have managed to preserve our pawn structure while keeping the bishop pair.}) (5... Nc6 {is also met with} 6. a3 $1 {[%csl Rb4] going for their bishop.} Bxd2+ 7. Qxd2 {a great advantage of these lines is that White often wins the bishop pair without spoiling their pawn structure (unlike Nimzo where ...Bxc3 is a very common motif).} g5 (7... Ne4 $6 {runs into} 8. Bxd8 Nxd2 9. Bxc7 Nxc4 10. e4 $14 {[%csl Gc7,Gd4,Ge4,Gf1] with a stable center/two bishop advantage for White.}) 8. Bg3 Ne4 9. Qd3 Nxg3 10. hxg3 d6 11. e3 $14 {[%csl Gc4,Gd4,Ge3,Gg3,Rh6][%cal Gg1e2,Ge2c3,Gf1e2,Ge1c1,Gh1h6] White retains more space and a better pawn structure and thus, keeps a small edge.}) 6. Bg3 Ne4 7. Ngf3 {[%csl Rg5,Rh6] While Black has managed to gain some initiative in the past couple of moves, they have made some concessions on the Kingside.} h5 {[%cal Gh5h4] Black continues to expand on the Kingside.} (7... g4 $6 {It seems like they are winning a piece but White has the strong counterpunch with} 8. a3 $1 {[%csl Rb4][%cal Ga3b4] a theme that comes into play in a lot of these lines. We ask them to give up their bishop.} Nxg3 (8... gxf3 9. axb4 $18) 9. hxg3 Bf8 10. Nh4 Bg7 11. e3 h5 12. Bd3 {[%cal Gd1c2,Ye1g1,Gb2b4] we'll play Qc2 & 0-0-b4 next. White keeps a stable edge thanks to space and pawn structure here.}) (7... Nc6 8. a3 {as usual, we go for their bishop.} Bxd2+ 9. Nxd2 Nxg3 10. hxg3 Nxd4 {Black has won a pawn, but it comes at the cost of weakened dark-squares.} 11. Ne4 {here, they have to choose between two logical moves.} Nc6 (11... Nf5 {is weaker. After} 12. g4 $1 d5 13. cxd5 exd5 14. gxf5 dxe4 15. Qa4+ $1 {White remains better. A possible line is} c6 (15... Kf8 16. g4 $16 {[%csl Gf5,Gg4][%cal Ga1d1,Ga4e4]}) 16. Qxe4+ Qe7 17. Qd4 f6 18. g4 $18 {[%cal Gh1h3] there's too many weaknesses in Black's camp.}) 12. Qd2 f6 13. Qc3 $44 {[%csl Gc3,Ge4,Rf6][%cal Ge2e3,Ge1c1] White retains fantastic compensation thanks to their activity.}) (7... b6 {is met with the usual} 8. a3 Bxd2+ 9. Nxd2 Nxg3 10. hxg3 Bb7 11. Qc2 $14 {[%cal Ge1c1,Gd4d5,Ye2e4,Rc2c3,Rc3h8]}) (7... c5 8. d5 g4 9. a3 Ba5 {Black claims that they can preserve the bishop on the e1-diagonal with this particular move order. However, after} 10. Be5 $1 {they are the one who's struggling!} gxf3 (10... f6 11. b4 $16) 11. b4 cxb4 12. Nxe4 b3+ 13. Bc3 $14 {Black ends up having too many weaknesses.}) 8. Qc2 {forcing them to release the tension.} Nxd2 {the safest choice.} (8... d5 9. O-O-O {Black risks getting butchered here as we have a huge lead in development.} h4 $6 (9... Nxd2 10. Nxd2 Bxd2+ 11. Rxd2 $16) 10. Be5 f6 {this is playing with fire. White wins after} 11. cxd5 exd5 12. Nxe4 dxe4 13. Qxe4 Kf8 14. Nxg5 fxe5 15. Qg6 $18 {with a decisive attack for White.}) (8... f5 $6 9. O-O-O $1 Nxd2 10. Nxd2 h4 11. Be5 Rh6 12. d5 $14 {we keep a huge lead in development here.}) 9. Nxd2 Nc6 {keeping the e5-square in checking before playing ...h4.} (9... Bxd2+ 10. Kxd2 $1 {[%cal Rc2g6,Rh5h4,Rg3e5,Rf7f6] keeping the option of Qg6 alive.} h4 (10... Nc6 11. h4 $1 Nxd4 $6 12. Qc3 $18) 11. Be5 Rh6 12. d5 $14 {[%csl Ge5,Gf1] we maintain some pressure due to the lead in development and the advantage of the  pair.}) 10. h4 $1 {not giving them the time to play ...h4.} Nxd4 11. Qd3 Nf5 12. hxg5 {we have lost a pawn but as usual, the weaknesses in their camp offer sufficient compensation.} d6 $1 {only this precise move equalises.} (12... Nxg3 13. Qxg3 $14 {[%cal Ge2e3,Gf1d3]}) (12... Qxg5 {is bad. After} 13. Bxc7 {White is on top!} d6 (13... b5 14. O-O-O $14) 14. c5 Bxc5 (14... dxc5 15. O-O-O) 15. e4 $14 {White keeps healthy initiative.}) (12... Bxd2+ 13. Qxd2 Nxg3 14. fxg3 $14 {[%csl Rh5,Rh8][%cal Gg3g4,Gh1h8]}) 13. f4 {[%csl Gf4,Gg5]} Nxg3 14. Qxg3 Bxd2+ 15. Kxd2 e5 16. e3 {Black is still far away from being in a risk-free position. We still keep somewhat extra space.} Bf5 {this natural move is an error. After} (16... Be6 $1 {this precise move equalises.} 17. Bd3 Qd7 18. Raf1 {[%cal Gf4f5]} Qa4 {this precise move solves Black's problems. The position fizzles out. A sample line is} 19. f5 Bxc4 20. Bxc4 Qxc4 21. g6 fxg6 22. Qxg6+ Qf7 23. g4 h4 24. Rh3 $11) 17. Bd3 Bxd3 18. Kxd3 {White is surprisingly slightly better. We keep more space while they cannot attack our king.} d5 {this natural move can be met with} ({The simple but not-obvious} 18... Qe7 $1 19. Qh3 d5 20. cxd5 $1 Rd8 {equalises. Still, after} 21. e4 c6 22. Rae1 cxd5 23. Kc2 {there's some game left.}) 19. Ke2 $14 {things can turn out to be dangerous for Black super soon as the natural} dxc4 $4 {runs into} 20. Rad1 Qe7 21. f5 $18 {[%csl Re8]} *

