{In the second chapter, we'll cover all of Black options after 3...Bb4 4.Nd2 except for ...h6, which was covered in the previous chapter.} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Bg5 Bb4+ 4. Nd2 {the starting point of this chapter.} c5 {This has been played 4 times against Grischuk! Black wants to undermine our center.} (4... Ne4 $6 {This initiates a tactical sequence that ends up in White's favour after} 5. Bxd8 Bxd2+ 6. Qxd2 Nxd2 7. Bxc7 Nxc4 8. Rc1 Nxb2 9. Bd6 Nc6 10. e4 $16 {[%csl Ra8,Rb2,Rc8,Gd4,Gd6,Ge4,Re8,Gf1,Gg1][%cal Rc6d4,Rd6e5,Gd4d5] we end up having a huge center. Their king is stuck in the center.}) (4... d5 {another extremely logical move. Here, I recommend the novel} 5. Rc1 $5 {[%cal Gc2c4,Gc1c4] preventing ...dxc4 ideas convincingly.} h6 (5... dxc4 6. Rxc4 Nc6 7. e3 $14 {[%cal Gg1f3,Ga2a3]}) 6. Bh4 {[%csl Rd8][%cal Gh4d8]} O-O (6... g5 $5 7. Bg3 Ne4 {This is met with a thematic response.} 8. Ngf3 g4 9. a3 $1 {[%csl Rb4] Once they lose the dark-squared bishop, Black's position loses its charm.} gxf3 $4 (9... Nxg3 10. hxg3 $16) 10. axb4 Nxg3 11. hxg3 fxe2 12. Qxe2 $18) 7. Ngf3 {Black may choose from a few decent options here.} Nbd7 {played in two OTB games.} (7... b6 8. e3 Bb7 9. cxd5 exd5 10. Bd3 $14 {[%cal Ge1g1,Gf3e5,Gf2f4] White keeps a better pawn structure and more active pieces.}) (7... dxc4 $1 8. Rxc4 Be7 {this is what equalises according to Stockfish. However, after} 9. e4 (9. Qc1 $5 c6 10. e3 b6 11. Rc2 Bb7 12. Be2 Nbd7 13. O-O Rc8 14. Rd1) 9... b6 10. Qc2 c5 11. Bxf6 gxf6 12. e5 (12. dxc5 bxc5 13. Rc3 {is a safe backup.}) 12... f5 13. g4 $5 $13 {[%csl Rh6][%cal Gh1g1,Gd2e4,Gc2d2,Gd2h6] the position is far from clear.}) 8. e3 Be7 (8... b6 $6 {can be met with the thematic} 9. cxd5 exd5 10. Bb5 $16 {[%csl Rc6]}) 9. Qc2 {keeping the option of playing cxd5 at any point alive.} b6 (9... c5 10. dxc5 Nxc5 11. cxd5 $14 {[%csl Rc5][%cal Gh4d8] They face issues with their knight.}) 10. cxd5 Nxd5 11. Bxe7 Qxe7 12. e4 Nb4 13. Qa4 $14 {[%csl Ga3] we end up keeping a space advantage.}) (4... b6 {is met with the thematic} 5. a3 Bxd2+ 6. Qxd2 Ne4 (6... Bb7 7. f3 $14) 7. Bxd8 Nxd2 8. Bxc7 Nxc4 9. b3 Na5 10. b4 Nb3 11. Rd1 $14 {White keeps some pressure due to their bishop pair advantage.}) (4... O-O 5. Ngf3 d5 6. Rc1 $14 {This is a better version of the same line with ...h6-Bh4 included for White.}) 5. dxc5 $1 Bxc5 6. e3 h6 7. Bh4 O-O ({starting out with} 7... b6 {doesn't change much. After} 8. Ngf3 Bb7 9. Be2 O-O {we transpose.}) 8. Ngf3 {White plays for a micro-pressure in these lines. Black remains solid but our pieces have more potential to move around here.} Nc6 ({starting out with} 8... b6 {also makes sense.} 9. Be2 {White's play remains consistent though.} (9. g4 $5) 9... Bb7 10. O-O Be7 (10... Nc6 11. a3 a5 {Black delays ...Be7. Here, we can try to capitalise on it by playing} 12. Ne4 $5 g5 {I don't expect anyone to play like this in a practical game.} (12... Be7 $6 {is weaker now. After} 13. Nxf6+ Bxf6 14. Bxf6 Qxf6 15. Qxd7 $16 {White is significantly better.}) 13. Nxc5 bxc5 14. Bg3 Ne4 15. Bd6 Nxd6 16. Qxd6 Qe7 17. Rfd1 $11 {[%cal Gd1d6,Yf3e1,Ye1d3] the position fizzles out soon.}) 11. a3 d6 12. b4 Nbd7 13. Nd4 Rc8 14. Rc1 {[%cal Gd1b3,Gf2f3,Gh4f2,Ge3e4] we keep the usual pressure due to the extra space.}) 9. Be2 b6 {delaying ...d5.} (9... d5 10. O-O Be7 11. Qc2 {Black remains quite solid here but we keep some pressure since our pieces remain more active.} e5 $6 (11... Bd7 12. Rac1 Rc8 13. Qb1 {[%cal Gf1d1,Gc4d5,Gh4e7] we keep some thematic pressure in these lines.}) 12. Bxf6 $5 (12. Rfd1 $1 Be6 13. Bxf6 Bxf6 14. cxd5 Bxd5 15. Ne4 $16 {would have been more precise.}) 12... Bxf6 13. cxd5 Qxd5 14. Rfd1 $14 {White keeps some pressure thanks to the control of the light-squares and the potential knight jumps. This was played in the following game :1-0 (57) Puranik,A (2627)-Aditya,M (2595) Sant Boi de Llobregat op 4th 2023 (7)}) 10. a3 Be7 $1 {keeping things safe.} (10... a5 $6 11. g4 $1 $16 {[%cal Gg4g5,Gd1c2,Ge1c1,Gh1g1] this can turn out to be extremely dangerous for Black.}) 11. O-O Bb7 12. Qb1 {[%cal Gb2b4,Yb1b2,Gf1d1,Ga1c1] preparing b4/vacating the d1-square for the rook. A potential line is} Nh5 13. Bxe7 Qxe7 14. b4 Nf6 15. Rd1 Rfd8 16. Qb2 {White keeps some pressure due to their spatial advantage on the Queenside.} *

