{In the third chapter, we cover the 3...h6 4.Bh4 g5!? option for Black.} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Bg5 h6 {Black immediately targets the bishop on g5.} 4. Bh4 g5 {the most ambitious move. Black expands on the Kingside and blocks the bishop on h4. While this reduces our activity, they weaken their Kingside.} 5. Bg3 {here, they can choose between three options.} h5 $5 {the most ambitous. They go for our bishop!} (5... Ne4 {this allows White to obtain a stable and a comfortable position after} 6. Nc3 Nxg3 7. hxg3 Bg7 8. e3 {[%csl Gc4,Gd4,Ge3,Gg3][%cal Gh1h6] I think these structures are quite pleasant to play as White.} d6 9. Qd2 c5 $5 {this is the best option for Black here. They try to undermine our center.} ({a slow move like} 9... O-O {can be met with} 10. O-O-O $14 {[%cal Gf1d3,Gf2f4] White is already better and shall soon start an attack on the Kingside.}) 10. d5 $5 exd5 {important!} ({starting out with} 10... O-O {runs into} 11. Rd1 {[%cal Gd5e6] where White is already slightly better placed. A possible line is} Re8 12. dxe6 Bxe6 13. Bd3 Nd7 14. Nge2 Ne5 15. b3 Nxd3+ 16. Qxd3 $14 {[%csl Gc3,Gd3,Ge2] White keeps a solid positional grip over the position.}) 11. Nxd5 Be6 $1 {this move equalises concretely.} (11... Nc6 12. Ne2 Be6 13. Nec3 {[%cal Gc3b5,Gf1e2] leads to an extremely comfortable position for White.}) 12. Ne2 Bxd5 13. Qxd5 Bxb2 (13... Qb6 {perhaps the best choice for Black.} 14. Rb1 Qa5+ {[%cal Ra5a2] this way, Black doesn't face the Nc3 resource anymore.} 15. Nc3 Bxc3+ 16. bxc3 Qxc3+ 17. Kd1 Nd7 18. Rxb7 Qa1+ 19. Ke2 {[%csl Ra8,Rd7]} Qxa2+ 20. Ke1 Qa1+ $11 {Both sides can't avoid a repetition.}) (13... Qa5+ 14. Qd2 Qxd2+ 15. Kxd2 $14 {[%csl Rd6,Rh6][%cal Ge2c3,Gg3g4] leads to a pleasant endgame for White.}) 14. Rb1 Bg7 15. Qe4+ Qe7 {this might seem quite convincing for Black too but after} (15... Kf8 $1 {this concrete move equalises. White has to play 16.Rxb7, which ends in a repetition.} 16. Rxb7 Nd7 17. Rxd7 Qa5+ 18. Kd1 Qa4+ 19. Kd2 Qb4+ 20. Kd1 $11) 16. Qxe7+ Kxe7 17. g4 $5 Nd7 18. Ng3 {White keeps some pressure. A possible line is} Rhd8 (18... Rhb8 $6 19. Nf5+ Kf8 20. g3 $14 {[%cal Gf1g2]}) 19. Nf5+ Kf8 20. Nxh6 {[%cal Gh6f5,Gh1h7] White keeps some pressure.}) (5... Bb4+ 6. Nd2 {transposes to the previous chapters.}) 6. f3 {[%cal Gg3f2] making space for the bishop.} c5 {The best move for Black. They immediately go for our center.} (6... h4 7. Bf2 d5 {here, we should sacrifice a pawn for activity by playing} (7... c5 {wrong move order. After} 8. dxc5 Na6 9. e4 $16 {[%csl Gc4,Ge4][%cal Gd1d2,Gb1c3] we keep a huge advantage.}) 8. e4 dxe4 9. Nc3 exf3 $6 (9... c5 10. d5 $5 $13 {leads to complex positions too.}) 10. Nxf3 $14 {the resulting positions are quite tricky for Black.} Bh6 (10... Rg8 11. Qc2 $18 {[%cal Ge1c1]}) 11. Bd3 b6 (11... Ng4 12. Bg1 $16) 12. Qe2 Bb7 13. d5 $16 {Black is busted!}) (6... d5 7. Nc3 h4 (7... c5 8. e3 h4 9. Bf2 {transposes.}) 8. Bf2 c5 9. e3 Rg8 (9... Nc6 10. Nh3 Rg8 {transposes.}) 10. Nh3 {In this structure with e3-f3, we often place our knights on h3.} Nc6 11. Be2 dxc4 12. O-O Bd7 13. Rc1 Qc7 14. Kh1 O-O-O 15. b3 $13 {Chaos emerges soon.}) 7. e3 h4 (7... d5 8. Nc3 {transposes.}) (7... cxd4 {the inclusion of cd-ed doesn't change anything. The positions after} 8. exd4 d5 9. Nc3 Nc6 10. Qd2 h4 11. Bf2 $13 {[%cal Gf2e3,Gg1h3] remain complex.}) 8. Bf2 d5 (8... Nc6 9. Nh3 Rg8 (9... d5 10. Be2 Rg8 {transposes.}) 10. d5 $1 $14 {White is able to clamp down space in the center.} Ne5 11. Nc3 d6 12. Nxg5 $1 {this concrete tactical detail solves our problems. After} Rxg5 13. f4 Rg6 14. fxe5 $14 {White remains better.}) 9. Nh3 $1 {we continue to delay Nc3.} Rg8 10. Be2 Nc6 11. O-O Qc7 {here, I recommend the rather unconvential} 12. Kh1 {a prophylactic response against ...Bd6. The positions remain complex.} Bd7 (12... Bd6 $6 {runs into} 13. Nc3 a6 14. dxc5 $16) 13. Na3 a6 14. dxc5 Bxc5 15. Rc1 Be7 16. cxd5 exd5 17. Nc2 $5 $13 {with a complex middlegame on the board. All 3 results are possible.} *

