{In the fourth chapter, we'll cover 3...h6 4.Bh4 and now the 'Benoni' setup with 4...c5.} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Bg5 h6 4. Bh4 c5 {Black wants to challenge our center immediately.} 5. d5 {we expand and go for the Benoni setup.} exd5 6. cxd5 d6 7. e4 {Black has two decent options here.} Be7 {the choice of most players.} (7... g5 {also makes sense.} 8. Bg3 Qe7 (8... Bg7 9. Nd2 $5 {[%cal Gf1d3,Gg1e2,Gd2c4] This is more flexible as we keep the opportunity to jump over to c4.} O-O 10. Bd3 b5 $5 {trying to undermine our center by expanding on the Queenside.} (10... Re8 11. Ne2 Qe7 12. Nc3 $16 {[%csl Gc3,Gd2,Rd6][%cal Ge1g1,Gd2c4] White has managed to stabilise.}) (10... Qe7 11. Ne2 Nbd7 {This setup is good against our knight on c3 but here, White can play} 12. O-O Nh5 13. Nc4 Ne5 14. Bxe5 Bxe5 15. a4 $5 {[%cal Yh5f4,Ge2g3] keeping a stable edge.}) 11. Ne2 c4 12. Bc2 Nh5 13. a4 {an ambitious sacrifice.} Bxb2 {natural, but weaker.After} (13... Nxg3 14. Nxg3 $13) 14. axb5 $1 Bxa1 15. Qxa1 {[%cal Gd2c4] the real complications begin!} f5 {trying to challenge our Queenside.} 16. exf5 Bxf5 17. Bxf5 Rxf5 18. O-O Nd7 19. Qb1 Qf6 20. Nxc4 $14 {their exposed king offers more than sufficient compensation for the missing king.}) 9. Nc3 $1 {forced, this time.} (9. Nd2 Nbd7 $1 $15 {[%cal Gf6d5,Rf8g7]}) 9... Nbd7 (9... a6 10. Bd3 {conveniently ignoring their threats.} b5 $6 (10... Nbd7 {this is a better choice for Black. After} 11. f4 gxf4 12. Bxf4 Rg8 13. Qe2 $13 {[%cal Ge1c1,Gg1f3] we end up having a complicated middlegame on the board.}) 11. e5 dxe5 12. Nf3 Nbd7 13. O-O Bg7 14. Re1 {[%csl Re5][%cal Ge1e8,Re8g8,Rd5d6,Gd3h7] Black faces problems with their center.}) 10. Bd3 Bg7 (10... a6 {transposes.}) 11. Nb5 {trying to take advantage of the opportunity to jump over to b5.} Nxe4 12. Bxe4 Qxe4+ 13. Qe2 Qxe2+ 14. Nxe2 O-O 15. Bxd6 $13 {[%csl Gb5,Gd6][%cal Rg7b2,Ga1d1,Rb5c7] with an objectively balanced but a practically complicated position. White will soon win an exchange.}) (7... Qa5+ 8. Qd2 $14 {[%csl Rd6][%cal Gb1d2,Gd2c4,Gh4g3] we don't mind trading the queens.}) (7... g6 {the traditional Benoni setup isn't great for Black. After} 8. Nc3 Bg7 9. Nf3 O-O 10. Nd2 $16 {[%csl Gd5,Ge4][%cal Gd1c2,Gf1e2,Ge1g1,Ra7a6,Ra2a4] White manages to stabilise the center.}) 8. Bg3 {getting out of ...Ne4/...Nxd5 ideas.} O-O (8... Qa5+ 9. Qd2 Qxd2+ 10. Nxd2 {[%cal Gf2f3,Gd2c4] as mentioned earlier, we don't mind trading the queens here.} Nh5 {going for our bishop. However, after} 11. f3 Nxg3 12. hxg3 f5 13. Bd3 fxe4 14. Nxe4 $14 {[%csl Re6,Rg6][%cal Ge1c1,Gg1e2,Gg3g4,Ye2f4] I think White keeps an easier game.}) (8... Nbd7 9. Nd2 O-O {transposes.}) 9. Nd2 {another important crossroads. We keep the knight on d2 and not c3 in these lines.} Nxe4 $5 {initiating a concete sequence.} (9... Re8 10. Bd3 Nbd7 (10... Bf8 11. Ne2 $14 {White consolidates.}) 11. a4 $1 {preventing any counterplay with ...b5.} a6 (11... c4 12. Bc2 Nc5 13. Ne2 $14) 12. Ne2 Nh5 {the inclusion of a4 & ...a6 favours White.} 13. O-O Nxg3 14. Nxg3 $1 Bf6 15. Qc2 Rb8 16. a5 Ne5 17. Be2 b5 18. axb6 Qxb6 19. Ra2 $13 {[%csl Ra6,Rb2][%cal Gg1h1,Gf2f4,Gg3h5] with a complicated middlegame on the board.}) (9... Nbd7 10. Bd3 Re8 {transposes.}) (9... Bd7 $5 {played in one of the two OTB games in this line.} 10. Bd3 b5 11. h3 {[%cal Gg1e2,Gg3h2] vacating the h2-square for the bishop.} c4 12. Bc2 Na6 13. Ne2 {White is able to stabilise their center.} Nb4 $6 (13... Nc5 14. O-O Re8 15. f4 Bf8 16. Bh4 $14 {we keep an advantage due to the extra space in the center.}) (13... Rc8 14. O-O Re8 $5 15. a3 Nc5 16. f4 Bf8 17. Bh4 $5 {Black can liquidate with ...Nd3 but they still need to play a string of precise moves here. This is a total 3-result position.}) 14. Bb1 Nh5 15. Bh2 $14 {we are able to stabilise here.}) 10. Nxe4 f5 {Black wins the piece back of course.} 11. Nd2 f4 12. Bd3 {While they win our dark-squared bishop, it comes at the cost of weakened light-squared on the Kingside.} fxg3 13. hxg3 Nd7 14. Ngf3 Bf6 {here, I recommend} 15. Qc2 Ne5 16. Nxe5 Bxe5 17. O-O {[%cal Ga1e1]} Qf6 18. Rae1 {White goes for concrete play down the Kingside!} g5 {trying to prevent f4.} (18... Bf5 19. Nf3 Bxd3 20. Qxd3 Bxb2 21. Qb5 Bd4 22. Qxb7 $14 {[%csl Rd6][%cal Ge1e6] we keep some pressure here.}) (18... Bxb2 $2 19. Ne4 Qe5 20. Re2 $16 {wins material.}) 19. Nf3 Bxb2 20. Re3 $44 {[%cal Gf1e1] White keeps compensation down the e-file.} *

