{In the fifth chapter, we cover the Miscallenous systems arising after 3...h6 4.Bh4.} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Bg5 h6 4. Bh4 Be7 {an extremely solid way of playing. They play in the 'QGD' fashion.} (4... Bb4+ 5. Nd2 {transposes to the previous chapters.}) (4... d5 5. cxd5 g5 {the only independent try, though it is isn't great. After} (5... exd5 6. Nc3 {transposes to the 'QGD' transposition.}) 6. Bg3 exd5 7. Nc3 $14 {White remains slightly better.}) ({starting out with} 4... b6 {also makes sense.} 5. Nc3 Bb7 6. Qc2 {[%cal Ge2e4] we want to build a massive center.} Bb4 (6... Be7 {allows to execute our plans with} 7. e4 c5 $5 {trying to undermine our center. Here, I propose the fighting} (7... Nc6 {This was played in the only OTB game between GMs. However, after} 8. O-O-O Nh5 $6 9. Bxe7 Qxe7 10. Nf3 $16 {White managed to win convincingly in 1-0 (23) Grischuk,A (2719)-Iniyan,P (2523) Chess.com INT 2024}) 8. Bxf6 Bxf6 9. e5 cxd4 10. exf6 dxc3 11. fxg7 Rg8 12. Qh7 Ke7 13. bxc3 $44 {leading to a big mess.}) 7. e3 ({this time,} 7. f3 {doesn't work. After} c5 $15 {Black is better. There is no d5 option for White.}) 7... g5 8. Bg3 Bxc3+ (8... Ne4 9. Nge2 h5 10. Be5 f6 11. d5 $16 {[%csl Re4,Rg6][%cal Gc2g6] Black has problems with their king.}) 9. Qxc3 Ne4 10. Qc2 {we are already slightly better here.} d6 11. f3 Nxg3 12. hxg3 $5 {[%csl Rh6][%cal Gf1d3,Gg1e2,Gg3g4,Gh1h6] we'll play Bd3-Ne2-0-0-0-g4 next. White keeps some pressure due to their space.}) 5. Nc3 {We continue to develop normally.} d5 {the 'QGD' fashion.} (5... c5 6. dxc5 $1 Na6 $5 (6... Bxc5 7. Nf3 Nc6 8. e3 {[%cal Gf1e2,Ge1g1,Yd1c2,Ga2a3,Gb2b4,Ga1c1] We have seen these structures previously. White keeps some pressure here due to the extra space in the center.}) 7. Qc2 Nxc5 8. b4 Na6 9. a3 {[%csl Ga3,Gb4,Gc4][%cal Gg1f3] we'll develop with Nf3 next. White keeps some space. Watch out for your e4-ideas.}) (5... O-O {allows White to expand with} 6. e4 $5 {[%csl Gd4,Ge4] building a massive center.} d5 {principled. They challenge with our center.} (6... d6 7. Nf3 Nc6 8. Be2 e5 9. d5 Nb8 10. O-O $13 {[%cal Ga2a3,Gb2b4,Rh4f6] with a weird lookng KID structure on the board. You would play Bxf6 next (to avoid getting hit with Nxe4) and expand on the Queenside later. Note that 10...Nxd5 runs into 11.Nxd5 Bxh4 12.Nxh4 Qxh4 13.Nxc7.}) 7. e5 Ne4 (7... Nfd7 {is too passive. After} 8. Bxe7 Qxe7 9. Nf3 $14 {White remains better.}) 8. Bxe7 Qxe7 9. cxd5 Nxc3 10. bxc3 exd5 11. Bd3 f6 12. f4 fxe5 13. fxe5 {[%cal Gd1h5,Rg1f3] we keep a massive center. White wants to play Nf3 or Qh5 next.}) 6. cxd5 Nxd5 $5 {playing in the 'Tartakower' style. Black wants to trade both sets of minor pieces. Here, I recommend playing} (6... exd5 {transposes to the 'QGD' lines.}) 7. Bxe7 Qxe7 8. Qc2 O-O 9. Rc1 $5 {[%cal Gg1f3] White keeps some pressure on the Queenside. We'll follow up with Nf3 & e3 next.} *

