{In the seventh chapter, we'll cover the aboluste main line of the QGD arising with 5...Be7 & 6...h6.} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Bg5 d5 4. cxd5 exd5 5. Nc3 Be7 6. e3 h6 7. Bh4 c6 {The major tabiya in the QGD system. Our setup here is going to be play Bd3-h3-Nf3-Qc2. Basic points to remember here- 1) Black's c8 bishop should be kept on the board at all costs. If we manage to do that, we'll be better. 2) White would love to play Ne5 or Rab1-b4 in these structures. 3) The dark-squared bishop is best placed on the b8-h2 diagonal.} 8. Bd3 O-O {here, I recommend the extremely rare} (8... Nbd7 9. Bg3 O-O {transposes.}) (8... Ne4 {this is too hasty. The resulting positions after} 9. Bxe7 Qxe7 10. Bxe4 dxe4 11. Nge2 O-O 12. Qc2 {are very easy to play as White. The pawn on e4 is weak.} Bf5 (12... f5 13. Nf4 Kh7 14. h4 $14) 13. O-O Nd7 14. d5 $14 {[%csl Rb7,Rc6,Re4,Rf5][%cal Ge2d4,Ge2f4,Gc3d5] Black will face issues with their structure.}) 9. Bg3 $5 {getting rid of ...Ne4/Nh5 ideas. White wants to play h3-Qc2-Nf3 in some order. The bishop is best placed on this diagonal.} Re8 $5 {[%cal Gc6c5] keeping the idea of playing an early ...c5.} (9... c5 {a typical reaction here. However, the positions arising after} 10. dxc5 Nc6 11. Nge2 Bxc5 12. O-O {are very easy to play as White. Their d5-pawn remains weak.} Bg4 {preparing ...d4.} (12... Qe7 13. Re1 $14 {[%cal Ge2f4] White keeps a stable strategic edge.}) 13. Rc1 d4 14. h3 $1 {an important intermezzo!} Bh5 (14... Bxe2 15. Nxe2 Bb6 16. e4 Re8 17. f3 Nb4 18. Kh1 $14 {their d4-pawn and the bishop on b6 are a bit sketchy.}) 15. Nb5 $1 Bb6 16. e4 {[%cal Gb5d6] this structure is favourable for White.} Re8 17. f3 Ne5 18. Kh1 {[%cal Gd1b3]} Bg6 19. Bf2 {Black has to be very precise here in order to equalise.} Nxd3 20. Qxd3 Nxe4 {other moves end up them being worse.} 21. fxe4 Bxe4 22. Qg3 Bxg2+ 23. Qxg2 Rxe2 24. Qxb7 Rb8 25. Qf3 Rxb2 26. Bg3 Rxb5 $1 27. Qxf7+ Kh8 28. Bxb8 Qxb8 $11 {with dynamic equality. A fitting end to a long and complicated variation. However, it is Black who needs to show precision here.}) (9... Bg4 10. Nge2 c5 11. dxc5 Bxc5 12. O-O Nc6 {transposes.}) (9... Ne8 {a logical idea but can be comfortably met with} 10. Qc2 Nd6 11. Nf3 Nd7 12. O-O Nf6 13. h3 $14 {[%cal Ga2a4,Gf3e5] we keep the thematic edge. We want to play a4 or Ne5 next.}) (9... Nbd7 10. h3 $1 {[%cal Gg1f3] these structures are very comfortable for White.} b5 (10... Re8 11. Nf3 $14 {transposes.}) 11. a3 a5 12. Nf3 $14 {[%csl Rc6] Black has problems with their c6-pawn.}) 10. h3 $5 {vacating the h2-square for our bishop. At the same time, we prevent them from trading bishops with ...Bg4.} c5 {trying to take advantage of having the rook on e8.} (10... Bd6 11. Bxd6 Qxd6 12. Qc2 {[%csl Rc8][%cal Gg1f3,Ge1g1] we'll play Nf3 & 0-0 next. Black has problems with their bishop.}) (10... Nbd7 11. Nf3 $14 {[%cal Ge1g1,Ga1b1,Gb2b4,Rd7f8] with a simple and solid strategic advantage for White. We want to play Ne5 or Rab1-b4 next.}) (10... Bb4 {this has been played by a few GMs but I find this weak. After} 11. Nge2 Ne4 12. Bxe4 Rxe4 13. Be5 $5 {White keeps decent pressure. Some sample lines-} Qg5 (13... f6 14. Qb3 $1 a5 15. Bxb8 Rxb8 16. a3 $14 {[%csl Rb4][%cal Rb4c3,Gb3c3,Gb2b4] they'll have to give up their bishop.}) 14. O-O Bxc3 15. Nxc3 Bxh3 16. Bg3 Rxe3 17. Ne2 $14 {Black will have to give up their rook.}) 11. Nf3 Nc6 12. O-O {now that the king is out of the danger on the e-file, we threaten dxc5.} cxd4 {trying to dissolve the tension before we play dxc5.} (12... a6 13. Rc1 cxd4 14. Nxd4 $14 {is a better version of the text for White.}) 13. Nxd4 Nxd4 14. exd4 {[%csl Rc8,Rd5][%cal Gf1e1,Ga1c1,Gd1b3] the position might look balanced on the first sight, but Black faces some pressure due to our lead in development. A possible line is} Bd6 (14... Be6 15. Nb5 $16) 15. Bh4 $1 Bb8 (15... Be6 16. Bc2 $14 {[%cal Gd1d3]}) 16. Qb3 a6 17. Na4 b5 18. Nc5 g5 19. Bg3 $14 {with easier play for White.} *

