{In this chapter, we will cover the trendy 7...Bg4 variation in the QGD.} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Bg5 d5 4. cxd5 exd5 5. Nc3 Be7 6. e3 h6 7. Bh4 Bg4 $5 {This move was popularised after Carlsen's win over Parham Maghsoodloo in 2023. Black wants to eliminate their light-squared bishop.} 8. Qc2 {simple and strong. This keeps an eye out on the c5-break.} O-O 9. h3 {pushing the bishop back.} Be6 (9... Bh5 {this has been played by GM Bartel in two games. Howevr, after} 10. Bxf6 Bxf6 11. Qf5 $1 {White wins a pawn. A possible line is} Bg6 12. Qxd5 Qe7 13. Qc4 Rd8 14. Nge2 $14 {[%cal Ge2f4,Gf1e2] we'll play Nf4 & Be2 next. Black doesn't have full compensation for the missing pawn.}) 10. Nge2 $5 {I find this rare move to be quite effective.} c5 {the most natural continuation. Black strikes in the center.} (10... Nh5 {this is thematic but weak in this case. After} 11. Bxe7 Qxe7 12. g4 Nf6 13. O-O-O {Black risks running into an attack on the Kingside. If they play the natural} c5 {we can play} 14. dxc5 Qxc5 15. Bg2 Nc6 16. Kb1 $14 {[%csl Rd5] maintaining pressure against the IQP.}) (10... Ne4 11. Bxe7 Qxe7 12. Nxe4 dxe4 13. Nf4 $14 {[%csl Re4] Black ends up with a big weakness in the center..}) (10... c6 {can be met with} 11. Nf4 Bc8 12. Bg3 {as we'll see repetatively, these structures are quite pleasant for White. We'll play 0-0-Bd3-Rfe1-Rab1-b4/Na4 next.}) 11. dxc5 Nc6 $1 12. Rd1 {[%csl Rd5] targeting the isolani.} Bxc5 13. a3 {Black has two choices here.} Be7 {the safer choice.} (13... g5 {trying to change the nature of the position.} 14. Bg3 Qe7 15. h4 $5 {we start attacking them now!} Rfd8 16. hxg5 hxg5 17. Na4 Bd6 18. Bxd6 Qxd6 19. Nc5 Rdc8 20. f4 (20. Ne4 $1 Nxe4 21. Qxe4 {White keeps some pressure after} dxe4 22. Rxd6 Rd8 23. Rxd8+ Rxd8 24. Ng3 {[%csl Re4,Rg5][%cal Gg3f5,Re6d5,Gh1h5]}) 20... gxf4 21. Nxf4 Ne5 22. b4 b6 23. Rh6 {Black needs to be extremely precise in these lines.} Neg4 (23... Qe7 24. Be2 bxc5 25. Rxd5 $5 {[%cal Re5g4,Gd5g5] with a big mess OTB.}) 24. Rg6+ $5) (13... Rc8 $6 14. Nf4 {offers us a stable advantage.}) 14. Nf4 d4 15. Nxe6 fxe6 16. Bc4 {It seems like White has a huge advantage but Black survives with} Qb6 $1 {the only move to stay in the game.} 17. Bxf6 Rxf6 (17... Bxf6 18. Na4 $14) 18. Ne4 Rff8 $1 19. exd4 Nxd4 20. Qb1 {I think despite the lack of enthusiasm from the engine, White keeps some pressure here due to the weak e6-pawn.} *

