{In the ninth chapter, we'll cover all options except 6...h6 in the QGD.} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Bg5 d5 4. cxd5 exd5 5. Nc3 Be7 6. e3 {the starting point of this chapter.} O-O {One of the three logical ways to play in the position.} (6... c6 {is the other way to play here.} 7. Bd3 {our setup remains consistent throughout.} Nbd7 (7... O-O {transposes.}) (7... Bg4 {is too early. After} 8. Qb3 Qb6 9. Qc2 $14 {[%cal Gh2h3,Gg5f4,Rg4e6,Gg1f3] we keep an edge. White will head over to their thematic plan of h3 & Bf4 next.}) (7... h6 8. Bh4 {transposes to the previous chapter.}) 8. h3 {sticking to the plan that we discuss in the previous chapter.} Nf8 (8... O-O 9. Nf3 {transposes.}) 9. Bf4 {avoiding ...Ng6-h6 ideas.} Ne6 ({this makes a lot of sense too.} 9... Ng6 10. Bh2 Bd6 11. Bxd6 Qxd6 12. Nf3 O-O 13. Qc2 $5 {[%cal Ge1g1,Gh1e1,Ga1c1,Ya1b1,Yb2b4,Yc3a4,Re3e4] we keep a stable edge here as well. Don't let them play ...Ne4 without having to worry about counteplay on the Queenside.}) 10. Be5 O-O 11. Nf3 g6 $5 12. O-O Ng7 {While they are able to swap their bad bishop with ...Bf5 next, Black had to spend a lot of time in doing so.} 13. Na4 Bf5 14. b4 $14 {[%cal Ga4c5,Gb4b5] White obtains the usual play on the Queenside.}) 7. Bd3 Re8 $5 {delaying ...Nbd7/c6. This doesn't change much.} (7... c6 8. Nf3 Nbd7 (8... Re8 {transposes.}) (8... h6 9. Bf4 $14 {[%cal Gh2h3] we'll play h3-Qc2-0-0 in some order next.}) (8... Bg4 {is rushed as usual. After} 9. Qb3 $14 {[%cal Gf3e5] we remain better.}) 9. h3 {preparing Bf4.} Ne4 (9... Re8 {transposes.}) 10. Bf4 $14 {[%csl Rb7][%cal Re4c3,Rb2c3,Ga2a4,Ga4a6,Yc3c4] we keep a stable edge here. ...Nxc3 bxc3 structures favour White.}) 8. Nf3 Nbd7 (8... c6 9. Qc2 {sticking to the usual setup.} Nbd7 (9... h6 10. Bf4 $14 {we'll play the thematic h3 & 0-0 next.}) 10. h3 {preparing Bf4. We don't have to worry about ...Nh5 anymore.} Ne4 (10... Nf8 11. O-O Ng6 {this plan never works due to} 12. Ne5 $16 {[%cal Gf2f4]}) 11. Bf4 Ndf6 12. O-O Bd6 13. Ne5 $14 {[%cal Ga2a4,Ga4a5] White will play Rfe1-f3 or Nce2-a4-a5 next.}) (8... h6 9. Bf4 {as usual, we prefer the h2-b8 diagonal over the h4-d8 diagonal for the bishop.} c5 {the only way to challenge us.} (9... Bd6 10. Bxd6 Qxd6 11. h3 $14 {[%csl Rc8] White keeps the usual edge here.}) 10. dxc5 Bxc5 11. O-O Nc6 12. h3 {preventing ...Bg4.} a6 (12... d4 {is a bit rushed due to} 13. Na4 Bd6 14. Bxd6 Qxd6 15. Bb5 $14) 13. Rc1 Ba7 (13... Bd6 14. Bxd6 $14 {1-0 (78) Vidit,S (2719)-Bluebaum,M (2672) Baku 2023}) 14. Ne2 Qb6 15. Rb1 Ne4 16. b4 Qd8 17. Bc2 $14 {[%cal Ga2a4,Rb4b5] with some pressure around the IQP.}) 9. h3 {the usual response. White prevents ...Bg4 and vacates the h2-square for the bishop.} c6 (9... Nf8 10. Qc2 Ng6 11. O-O $14 {[%cal Gf3e5] Ne5 is coming up next. We don't have to worry about ...h6.}) 10. Bf4 $5 {going for the intended setup.} Nf8 11. Qc2 Ng6 (11... Bd6 12. Bxd6 Qxd6 13. O-O $14 {[%csl Rc8][%cal Ga1b1,Gb2b4] Black has the usual problem with their bishop.}) (11... Be6 12. O-O $14 {[%csl Re6][%cal Ga1b1,Gb2b4,Ga2a3] the problem of bad bishop still persists.}) 12. Bh2 Bd6 13. Bxd6 Qxd6 {while 0-0 remains a decent option here, even better is} 14. O-O-O Be6 (14... b5 15. Kb1 $14 {[%csl Rc6]}) 15. Kb1 $14 {[%cal Gg2g4,Gd1b1] White keeps easier play as they can never break with ...c5 due to their pawn on d5.} *

