{In the 10th chapter, we'll cover the 5...Be6!? variation in the QGD.} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 d5 4. cxd5 exd5 5. Bg5 Be6 {This is my recommendation for Black in my next course on QGD! The positions are rich and fighting.} 6. e3 Nbd7 7. Bd3 c6 {here, instead of the usual Nf3, I recommend playing} 8. h3 $5 {[%cal Gg5f4] heading for the QGD structures.} (8. Nf3 h6 9. Bh4 g5 10. Bg3 Nh5 {offers Black great chances to play for a win.}) 8... Be7 9. Bf4 {[%csl Re6] our point. We are back in the QGD territory. The bishop on e6 is restricted.} O-O 10. Nge2 {[%cal Gf2f3] keeping the flexibility of playing f3 down the line.} Re8 {vacating the f8-square for the knight.} ({an early} 10... Nh5 $6 {can be met with} 11. Qc2 g6 12. Bh6 Ng7 13. O-O-O $16 {[%cal Gg2g4,Ge2f4] we have tremendous attacking chances here.}) 11. Bh2 {anticipating their ...Nh5 in advance.} g6 {[%cal Gf6h5] sticking with their plan.} (11... Nb6 12. O-O Bd6 13. Bxd6 Qxd6 14. Rb1 $14 {[%csl Re6][%cal Ge2f4,Gd1c2] with a stable positional edge for White.}) 12. O-O (12. Qc2 $5 {delaying 0-0. We want to castle long.} a6 {they'll play ...c5 only when we castle long. Otherwise, Black can play ...Nh5 once again.}) 12... Nh5 {[%cal Gh5g7,Ge6f5] they prepare ...Ng7-Bf5.} 13. g4 {taking the possibility of the bishop trade away from them.} Ng7 14. Kh1 $5 {[%cal Re2f4,Rd1f3,Ra1d1,Yf4e6,Rf3g2,Rf2f4,Re3e4] an useful prophylactic move.} Nb6 {[%cal Ge7d6] they prepare ...Bd6.} (14... h5 {only weakens the g6-square. After} 15. f3 $14 {[%csl Ge3,Gf3,Gg4,Gh3][%cal Gd1e1,Ge1h4] White keeps a solid spatial edge.}) (14... a5 15. Nf4 Nf8 {this is too passive. After} 16. Qf3 Bc8 17. Rad1 Nfe6 18. Nfe2 $14 {[%cal Gf3g2,Re3e4] we can break out with Qg2 & e4. Their piecess are quite inactive.}) 15. Nf4 Bd7 16. Qf3 {continuing with the intended plan.} Ne6 (16... a5 17. Rad1 {[%cal Gf1g1] we'll play Rg1 next. White will play prepare only after their pieces are optimally placed. The position remains blanaced but remains full of life.}) (16... Bd6 $6 17. Nfxd5 $14 {we win a pawn.}) 17. Nxe6 Bxe6 18. Qg2 {anticipating ...Bd6.} Bd6 19. f4 $14 {[%cal Gf4f5,Ga1e1] the point behind Qg2. We want to play f5 (with Rae1 included perhaps) next.} *

