{In the 11th chapter, we'll cover the 5...Bb4 system in the QGD.} 1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. cxd5 exd5 5. Bg5 Bb4 {After being neglected for a huge period of chess history,this system regained popularity in recent times. Black goes for active play. They want to play ...h6-g5-Ne4 next.} 6. e3 h6 {here, I propose the rare} 7. Bf4 $5 {looking to a play QGD-type like position. This avoids the active ...g5 plans.} O-O (7... g5 {doesn't work now on account of} 8. Be5 $1 {White has this additional option this time. After} Nbd7 9. Bxf6 Qxf6 10. Qb3 {Black ends up having a bunch of weaknesses.} Qb6 $5 {[%cal Gc7c6,Rb6b2,Gb4c3]} (10... Qd6 11. Bd3 $14 {[%csl Rc8,Rd5,Rd7][%cal Ga2a3,Gg1f3,Yd7f6,Gf3e5] we'll play Nf3 & a3 next. They have problems with their development.}) 11. h4 $5 {opening up the second front.} Rg8 12. hxg5 hxg5 13. Bd3 $14 {[%csl Rc8,Rd7][%cal Ge1c1,Gg1f3] Our king remains much safer than theirs.}) (7... Bd6 {this can be met with} 8. Bxd6 Qxd6 9. Bd3 {[%csl Gf5][%cal Gd3f5] with a good version of the QGD on the board. Black cannot eliminate their bad bishop.} O-O 10. Rc1 c6 11. Nge2 $14 {[%cal Gd1d2,Gf2f3,Ge1g1,Gh1e1,Ge2f4] we'll prepare f3-e4 down the line.}) (7... c5 $5 {an extremely rare move but perhaps the best one.} 8. Bb5+ Bd7 $1 {the right trade!} (8... Nbd7 $6 {is weaker. After} 9. Nge2 a6 10. Bxd7+ Bxd7 11. dxc5 Bxc5 12. Be5 $14 {We end up with a stable positional advantage.}) 9. Bxd7+ Qxd7 10. Nge2 cxd4 (10... Nc6 11. dxc5 $14) 11. Qxd4 Nc6 12. Qd3 $5 {[%csl Rd5] with tiny pressure for White around the center, though objectively speaking, Black faces no problems.}) (7... Bf5 {This is what Magnus chose against Keymer.} 8. Bd3 {we don't mind trading the bishops.} Bxd3 9. Qxd3 O-O {This is what Black was hoping for!} (9... c6 {a more precise move-order. After} 10. Nge2 {White has the extra option of playing} Nh5 $5 (10... Nbd7 11. f3 Nh5 12. Be5 {transposes.}) 11. Be5 Nd7 {here, I recommend playing} 12. f3 O-O 13. g4 {leading to a complicated positional mess. Some sample lines-} f6 (13... Qh4+ 14. Kd2 $14) 14. Bg3 Nxg3 15. hxg3 $5 {[%csl Gg4][%cal Ge1f2,Yf4g6,Yg6h4,Yh4f5,Gc3e2,Ge2f4] we'll play Nf4-Kf2 next.}) 10. Nge2 Nbd7 (10... c6 {This is what Gukesh chose against Keymer. However, after} 11. g4 $1 Ne4 12. h4 $14 {[%cal Ga2a3] White had a pleasant edge. We'll play g5 or a3 next.}) 11. a3 {forcing them to give up their bishop.} Bxc3+ 12. Qxc3 c6 13. a4 Nh5 14. O-O Nxf4 15. Nxf4 a6 16. b4 {[%cal Gb4b5] with an easier position for White. We want to undermine their queenside with b5 next.}) (7... Ne4 {without playing ...g5, there's no sting to this.} 8. Nge2 O-O 9. a3 $14 {[%csl Gf4] they don't have the thematic ...Nxg3 resource here. White keeps a comfortable edge after the pieces are traded on c3. The structures suit White.}) 8. Bd3 {[%csl Rc8] Black's problem of the c8-bishop persists.} c5 {trying to immediate challenge the center.} (8... c6 9. Nf3 Bg4 $5 (9... Re8 {This plan doesn't work with the bishop on b4. After} 10. O-O Ne4 11. Qb3 {[%cal Ga2a3] we keep a stable edge.}) 10. Qb3 {[%csl Rb4,Rb7][%cal Gb3b7,Gf3e5] Black ends up with the usual problems around the pawn on b7.}) 9. a3 $5 {a novelty, and a testing one.} Ba5 {the pawn on c5 is now a bit loose.} (9... Bxc3+ 10. bxc3 b6 {White has a thematic plan here.} 11. Ne2 {[%cal Ge2g3,Ge1g1,Gf2f3,Ge3e4]} Ba6 {Black always wants to get rid-off the light-squared bishops in these positions.} 12. Bxa6 Nxa6 13. O-O Re8 14. Qd3 Nc7 15. a4 $14 {[%csl Rc5,Rd5][%cal Ga4a5,Gf4e5,Gf1b1] White will exert pressure down the Queenside and on the d5-pawn.}) 10. Nge2 {[%cal Ge2c3,Gd4c5] avoiding ...Bxc3.} cxd4 (10... Nc6 $2 11. dxc5 $16) 11. exd4 Nc6 12. h3 $5 {[%cal Ge1g1,Gc3a4,Ya1c1,Yd3c2,Yb2b4,Gd1d3] I think White keeps micro-pressure here, though the computer evaluates this as zeroes.} *

