{In the 12th chapter, we will cover the infamous 6...Bf5 variation in the QGD.} 1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. cxd5 exd5 5. Bg5 c6 6. e3 Bf5 $5 {This line has a reputation for being extremely dull after 7.Qf3. Instead of proposing that, I offer a different solution.} 7. Bd3 {playing into Black's plan of trading the light-squared bishops. It isn't ideal, but there are a few tricks for us since we haven't committed to Nf3.} (7. Qf3 Bg6 8. Bxf6 Qxf6 9. Qxf6 gxf6 {This is a proper two-result position but White often times finds it hard to crack through here.}) 7... Bxd3 (7... Bg6 {this spoils Black's pawn structure unnecessarily. After} 8. Bxg6 hxg6 9. h4 {White remains better due to their pawn structure.} Be7 (9... Nbd7 10. Qc2 $14 {[%cal Gg1e2,Ge1c1] we'll play Nge2 & 0-0-0 next.}) (9... Na6 $5 10. Nf3 Nc7 11. Qb3 $14 {[%csl Rb7] they have issues with b7.}) 10. Qc2 {we'll play Nf3 if they play Na6. Or else, we'll play Nge2-Nf4 & 0-0-0.}) 8. Qxd3 {[%cal Gf2f3,Ge3e4] we'll be playing for f3-e4/g4 plans here.} Nbd7 {an useful move for Black.} (8... Be7 {starting with this doesn't change anything. After} 9. Nge2 O-O 10. O-O Nbd7 11. f3 {we transpose.}) (8... Bd6 {the bishop is misplaced here as they risk running into f3-e4.} 9. Nge2 O-O 10. f3 h6 11. Bh4 Nbd7 12. e4 $14 {[%csl Gd4,Ge4,Gf3] we keep a massive center and thus, keep a significantly better game.}) 9. Nge2 {[%cal Gf2f3] We keep our knight on e2 so that we can play f3 later.} Be7 (9... h6 10. Bh4 Bd6 {as usual, the bishop is misplaced here. After} (10... Be7 11. f3 O-O 12. O-O Re8 {transposes.}) 11. f3 $14 {[%cal Ge3e4] we remain better.}) 10. f3 O-O 11. O-O {both sides develop normally.} Re8 12. Bh4 $5 {waiting for Black to commit to a plan.} (12. Rad1 {can be met with} b5 13. Ng3 g6 $11 {[%csl Gc6] It's hard to attack c6-here.}) 12... h6 {basically saying 'Hey, let's transpose to one of the early h6 lines'.} (12... a5 $5 {can be now met with} 13. a4 Nf8 14. Bf2 Ne6 15. Kh1 {an useful move in general.} (15. e4 {is a bit premature. Black can target our dark-squares with} Nh5 16. Be3 Bg5 $5 {[%csl Rf4]}) 15... Qb6 (15... Rc8 16. e4 $5 $14) (15... Nh5 $5 16. Rad1 $5 {[%cal Ge3e4,Rg2g4] White will soon prepare e4 or g4.}) 16. e4 $14 {we keep an edge due to our massive center.}) (12... c5 13. Rfd1 $14 {[%csl Rc5,Rd5] They have problems with their pawn on d5.}) (12... b5 13. Rfc1 {[%csl Rc6][%cal Ga2a4] was our point. We want to place the rooks on c & a files!}) 13. Bf2 $5 {taking the bishop away from the danger zone.} Bd6 {Black improves their bishop.} (13... c5 {they have to always be careful with this as it weakens the d5-pawn. After} 14. Rad1 cxd4 15. Nxd4 $14 {[%csl Rd5] White is better due to the weak d5-pawn.}) (13... Rc8 14. e4 dxe4 15. fxe4 $5 {[%csl Gd4,Ge4] while they keep objective balance here, the position seems easier to play as White.}) 14. Ng3 {[%cal Gg3f5,Ge3e4] preparing Nf5/e4.} Rc8 $5 (14... b5 {weakens c6.} 15. Rac1 a5 16. Rc2 $14 {[%csl Rc6][%cal Gc3e2,Ye3e4,Gf1c1] we'll target the c6-pawn next.}) (14... g6 15. Rae1 $14 {[%cal Ge3e4] e4 should come up on the board soon.}) 15. Rac1 $5 {waiting for them to commit to a plan.} h5 {[%csl Rg3]} (15... a6 16. h3 {[%csl Ge3][%cal Gg3f5,Ge3e4,Rh3g4,Rf6g4] we prepare Rfe1-e4.}) 16. Rc2 g6 17. Rd1 $5 {[%cal Gg3f1,Gh2h3,Ge3e4] ...h4 will always be met with Nf1. If given a chance, we want to play e4.} Qe7 18. Nf1 Qe6 19. h3 $5 {[%cal Gc2e2,Ge3e4,Yc3e2,Ye2c1,Yc1d3,Gd3d2] we'll prepare Re2-e4 or Ne2-Nc1-Qd2-Nd3 next. THe position remains balanced with all to play for.} *

