{In the final chapter, we will cover all the other miscallenous options in the QGD.} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Bg5 d5 4. cxd5 exd5 5. Nc3 c6 6. e3 {the starting point of this chapter.} h6 (6... Bd6 {a fashionable system nowadays. Black brings their bishop out to the active square in one go.} 7. Bd3 O-O 8. Nf3 {against an early ...Bd6, this is quite effective. White keeps an eye on the weak e5-square.} Re8 9. O-O {here, they can choose from two setups.} Bg4 $5 {trying to eliminate their bad-bishop. This is principled, but it doesn't work here.} (9... Nbd7 {Black's usual developing scheme. This isn't challenging.} 10. Qc2 Nf8 11. h3 {[%csl Rd6] turns out, the bishop is actually misplaced here as they don't have the ...Ne4 resouce here. Further, they risk running into e4!} Ng6 {this is quite natural, but an instructive error.} (11... h6 12. Bh4 {transposes.}) 12. Rae1 {[%cal Ge3e4] we prepare e4! After} h6 13. Bxf6 Qxf6 14. e4 $1 Nh4 (14... dxe4 15. Nxe4 $16) 15. Nxh4 Qxh4 16. e5 Bb4 17. Rd1 $16 {[%cal Gf2f4] White has a big advantage thanks to their space advantage in the center.}) 10. Qb3 {[%csl Rb7][%cal Gb3b7] targeting b7.} Na6 $5 (10... Bxf3 $6 11. gxf3 {[%csl Gd3,Gf3,Gg5] this trade is actually favourable for White. The e4-square is now under our control. A possible line is} Qc8 12. Bh4 $1 Qh3 13. Bg3 Bxg3 14. hxg3 Nbd7 15. Ne2 $16 {[%csl Rh3][%cal Gb3b7,Ge2f4] All of this was played 1-0 (32) Mamedyarov,S (2726)-Annaberdiev,M (2467) Ankara 2024. White's king remains quite safe. We are going to kick their queen away with Nf4 next.}) 11. Rfe1 Bxf3 {still doesn't help them. After} (11... Qd7 12. Bxf6 $1 Bxf3 $4 13. gxf3 Qh3 14. Be5 Bxe5 15. dxe5 Rxe5 16. Ne2 $18 {We manage to stabilise the Kingside.}) 12. gxf3 Nc7 13. Kh1 Ne6 14. Bh4 $14 {White keeps a healthy edge.}) 7. Bh4 Bd6 $5 (7... Be7 {transposes to the usual QGD lines.}) (7... Bf5 {the inclusion of ...h6 & ...Bf5 doesn't change much. After} 8. Bd3 Bxd3 9. Qxd3 Be7 10. Nge2 Nbd7 11. f3 O-O 12. O-O {we transpose to the 6...Bf5 lines.}) 8. Bd3 O-O 9. Nf3 {our play remains quite similiar to the early ...Bd6 lines.} Nbd7 10. Qc2 Re8 11. O-O Nf8 12. h3 {[%cal Gh3g4] preventing ...Bg4. this might seem weird considering that ...g5 is now a threat but in fact, White wants them to play ...g5 as it would weaken their Kingside.} g5 {this is what we had been waiting for!} 13. Bg3 Bxg3 14. fxg3 {[%csl Rf6,Rf7,Rf8][%cal Gf1f8] their Kingside is now tremendously weak!} g4 {this is perhaps better but even after this, White remains better after} (14... Rxe3 {is a huge blunder. After} 15. Ne5 Qb6 16. Rxf6 Qxd4 17. Qf2 Qxe5 18. Rxf7 $18 {White crashes through!}) 15. Ne5 gxh3 16. Bf5 Be6 17. gxh3 $14 {[%csl Ge5,Gf5,Rf6,Rh6][%cal Gf1f6] our pieces remain more active.} *

